Raw sewage was discharged for more than 1,000 hours from a Thames Water overflow pipe into an environmental wetland at the Olympic Park last year, the Guardian can reveal. The combined sewer overflow (CSO) at Mulberry Court pumped untreated waste 91 times into the waterway that feeds into the River Lea. To April this year, the same CSO has so far discharged for 34 hours in 20 incidents. The area of wetlands in east London was created as part of the development of the Olympic Park. It was hailed as a legacy project to create a haven for plants, animals and insects for the public to enjoy. Dee Oâ€™Connell, a campaigner at the London Waterkeeper charity, tweeted live footage of one of the spills. ğŸ’© @electricadamâ€™s video of the raw sewage thatâ€™s being discharged right now into @noordinarypark wetlands @LDNWaterkeeper @Feargal_Sharkey @thameswater @NewhamLondon @LondonLegacy pic.twitter.com/XHdC0Q11E5 Data obtained by the Guardian and London Waterkeeper, which is campaigning for a â€œThames fit to swim inâ€, reveals the scale of the discharges that have been permitted by the Environment Agency. The sewage from the Mulberry Court CSO is discharged into a watercourse system in the Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park wetlands, which feed into the Lea. 1) Anglian Water Ownership: consortium of international investment funds Total directorsâ€™ pay: Â£5.3m Highest paid director: Â£1.97m, Scott Longhurst, former chief finance officer Total dividends 2010-19: Â£1.5bn 2) Northumbrian Water Ownership: Cheung Kong Infrastructure Holdings, a Hong Kong-based investment consortium Total directorsâ€™ pay: Â£1.96m Highest paid director: Â£930,000, Heidi Mottram, CEO Total dividends 2010-19: Â£1.192bn 3) Severn Trent Ownership: publicly listed on the London stock exchange Total directorsâ€™ pay: Â£4.3m Highest paid director: Â£2.4m, Liv Garfield, CEO Total dividends 2010-19: Â£2.009bn 4) Southern Water Ownership: privately owned, through a series of holding companies, by Greensands Holdi